                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1573">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.00/410.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-06-28T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 28, 1912—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your June 19. The marine detachment will not be withdrawn. Orders have been
                    issued authorizing, upon your recommendation, the rise of marines and infantry
                    to preserve order on election days in Panama and Colon. Should it become
                    indispensable for these forces to be used, you wall previously notify Panaman
                    authorities, informing them that such action is taken for the maintenance of
                    public order.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
